Bird rescued per air rescue service by North Sea drilling rig again released
A bird flown per air rescue service at the coast, that had been found exhausted on a North Sea drilling rig, was released again into nature.
The Wasserralle was flown last month with a helicopter to Aberdeen where it was nourished up by the Scottish animal protection organization SPCA into its rescue center in Alloa.
Colin Seddon, leader of the center, said: "this Wasserralle was probable a wintry migratory bird out of northern Europe, that through the strong winds over the North Sea delayed became".
Apparently the exhausted bird sought refuge on the drilling rig.
It added: "it could no longer further fly, why we with that ask for aid contacted became".
In its release, the Wasserralle was again fit and healthy.
